# MVP-001 – The First Clinical Product

**Status:** v1.0

**Type:** Product Definition

**Purpose**

This document defines the minimum product that Cortex must become before it is introduced into real clinical practice.

It does not describe the final vision.

It defines the first product worthy of daily use.

Every feature added before this milestone must move Cortex closer to that goal.

Everything else waits.

---

# Product Goal

On the first day of introductory training in General Practice, the physician should willingly choose Cortex during a real consultation.

Not because it is impressive.

Not because it uses AI.

Because it genuinely makes the consultation better.

---

# Success Statement

The MVP is successful when the physician finishes a consultation and thinks:

> "I do not want to do the next consultation without Cortex."

That—not downloads, users or AI capability—is the first success criterion.

---

# The Problem

General Practice is increasingly limited by cognitive and administrative overload.

Physicians are expected to simultaneously:

- think clinically
- remember guidelines
- remember referral criteria
- remember documentation requirements
- produce journals
- produce referrals
- produce certificates
- provide patient information

Most of this work adds little value to the patient encounter.

Cortex exists to remove that burden.

---

# The Promise

Cortex promises one thing.

Not faster documentation.

Not artificial intelligence.

Not automation.

Cortex promises a calmer consultation.

Everything else is secondary.

---

# The Experience

Using Cortex should feel like working alongside an experienced colleague.

Never like operating software.

The physician should feel:

- calmer
- more organised
- more confident
- less mentally overloaded

The patient should experience:

- more eye contact
- better communication
- greater presence
- greater confidence

---

# What The MVP Must Deliver

The MVP must support an entire consultation from beginning to end.

Including:

- structured consultation workflow
- adaptive questioning
- clinical decision support
- documentation
- referrals
- patient information
- consultation completion

without duplicate work.

---

# Clinical Scope

The MVP intentionally solves only a limited number of consultation types.

Breadth is sacrificed for depth.

The first pathways should represent different consultation patterns rather than many diagnoses.

Suggested initial pathways:

- Musculoskeletal complaint
- Acute symptom
- Chronic disease
- Mental health
- Preventive consultation

The objective is to validate the Workflow Engine—not maximise pathway count.

---

# Non-Goals

The MVP will NOT attempt to become:

- an electronic health record
- a scheduling system
- a billing system
- a messaging platform
- a prescription platform
- a patient database

Existing clinical systems already solve these problems.

Cortex complements them.

---

# Product Principles

Every MVP feature must satisfy at least one of the following:

- reduce cognitive load
- improve clinical quality
- improve consultation flow
- reduce administration
- improve patient communication

If it satisfies none of them, it should not be built.

---

# Definition of Quality

Quality is measured by:

- fewer forgotten clinical considerations
- higher quality journals
- higher quality referrals
- less duplicate documentation
- fewer unnecessary clicks
- lower cognitive effort

Never by feature count.

---

# Definition of Completion

The MVP is complete when a physician voluntarily chooses Cortex as the preferred consultation companion throughout an ordinary clinical day.

Not because Cortex can do everything.

Because it reliably improves everyday consultations.

---

# What We Optimise

The MVP does not optimise for:

- impressive demonstrations
- advanced AI
- complex automation
- marketing

The MVP optimises for:

- trust
- reliability
- simplicity
- calm
- consistency

---

# The First Principle

The MVP should solve ordinary consultations extraordinarily well.

Not extraordinary consultations adequately.

---

# Final Principle

Every roadmap discussion begins with one question:

> Will this make tomorrow's consultation genuinely better?

If the answer is uncertain...

the feature waits.
